SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 663
By Oliver
A RESOLUTION to honor and congratulate Meharry Medical
College upon the celebration of its 150th
anniversary.
WHEREAS, it is most appropriate that the members of this General Assembly should
honor and congratulate those venerable institutions of higher learning in the State of Tennessee
whose enduring achievements have garnered universal acclaim; and
WHEREAS, one such distinguished institution is Meharry Medical College, which in
2026 marks the 150th anniversary of its founding in Nashville, a sesquicentennial milestone that
commemorates a remarkable legacy of service, scholarship, and leadership; and
WHEREAS, Meharry Medical College was established in 1876 as the Medical
Department of Central Tennessee College, opening its doors in the basement of a local church
with eleven students and two faculty instructors and guided by the vision of co-founders Dr.
George W. Hubbard and Dr. William J. Snead; and
WHEREAS, the institution became the first medical school in the South for African
Americans and the first medical school in the South, historically Black or otherwise, to offer four-
year medical training; and
WHEREAS, the college's origins are rooted in an inspiring story of compassion: a young
Ohioan named Samuel Meharry, moved by an act of kindness from a freed couple early in his
life, went on to return their random act of kindness by pledging the cash and property necessary
to found Meharry Medical College; and
WHEREAS, over the course of its first five decades, Meharry Medical College expanded
its academic programs with the founding of the School of Dentistry in 1886 and the School of
Pharmacy in 1889 and graduating pioneering physicians and leaders whose service reached far
beyond Tennessee; and
