WHEREAS, among these trailblazers was Dr. Georgia Esther Lee Patton Washington,
who in 1893, became the first Black woman to graduate from Meharry and the first Black
woman licensed to practice medicine and surgery in the State of Tennessee; she was also the
first Meharry graduate to serve in Africa, returning in 1895 to practice in Memphis; and
WHEREAS, Meharry Medical College achieved autonomy in 1915 with its separate
charter, further advancing its mission, broadening its reach, and establishing itself as an
independent, enduring academic health sciences center; and
WHEREAS, since 1876, Meharry Medical College has been a pioneer in training Black
physicians, dentists, scientists, and healthcare leaders dedicated to advancing health access
and equity; from breaking barriers in medical education to leading public health innovation,
Meharry's legacy is rooted in service to communities often left behind; and
WHEREAS, Meharry Medical College is today home to five major schools: School of
Applied Computational Sciences, School of Dentistry, School of Global Health, School of
Graduate Studies, and School of Medicine, each providing an excellent education that prepares
leaders in medicine, dentistry, global health, computational sciences, and biomedical science
who are dedicated to the elimination of health disparities; and
WHEREAS, Meharry Medical College continues to advance its mission under the astute
leadership of its twelfth president and chief executive officer, James E.K. Hildreth, Sr., Ph.D.,
M.D., a nationally renowned leader whose commitment to health equity, research innovation,
and educational excellence has strengthened Meharry's role as a cornerstone of medical
education and community service; and
WHEREAS, in celebration of this sesquicentennial, Meharry has launched a yearlong
series of commemorations and initiatives, including Campaign 150, an ambitious strategy to
strengthen institutional excellence, expand community care, foster research and innovation, and
- 2 - 012115

prepare future generations of health professionals to meet the complex demands of tomorrow's
health challenges; and
WHEREAS, on this momentous occasion of 150 years of transformative leadership and
service, it is appropriate that we honor this historic institution for its indelible contributions to
education, health care, and the citizens of this State; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we honor and congratulate Meharry Medical College
on the celebration of its 150th anniversary, extending our best wishes for continued leadership,
excellence, and service in the years to come.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
